This is the universal event model (works for all analyzers/steps). It's the same "envelope" that each module uses to put its metrics in features, details in stats, and metadata in tags.

{
  "spec_version": "1.0",
  "ts": "<ISO8601 UTC timestamp>",
  "run_id": "<run_id>",
  "dataset_id": "<dataset_id-or-null>",
  "item_id": "<item_id-or-null>",
  "db_id": "<db_id-or-null>",

  "event_type": "<high_level_type>",   // e.g. "schema_analysis", "query_analysis", "execution"
  "name": "<analyzer_or_step_name>",   // e.g. "schema_validation", "sql_structure", "exec_probe"

  "status": "ok",                      // "ok" | "failed" | "skipped"
  "success": true,                     // boolean mirror for quick filters
  "duration_ms": <number>,
  "err": null,                         // if failed/skipped, short reason
  "features": {                        // analyzer-specific metrics (numbers, small arrays)
    "...": "..."
  },
  "stats": {                           // heavier details: lists, timings, debug, samples
    "collect_ms": <number>,
    "...": "..."
  },

  "tags": {                            // lightweight context: dialect, source, model, git_sha, etc.
    "dialect": "<sqlite|postgres|...>",
    "source": "<ddl|reflection|generated|...>",
    "git_sha": "<optional>",
    "analyzer_version": "<optional>"
  }
}
Usage Rules
Envelope keys are fixed: spec_version, ts, run_id, dataset_id, item_id, db_id, event_type, name, status, success, duration_ms, err, features, stats, tags.
status defines the overall event state; success is a convenient boolean duplicate.
features — short numerical/categorical indicators (what we aggregate by).
stats — detailed information/lists/raw examples (for drill-down).
tags — reference information (for slicing/filtering), does not affect success.
